hmhair</i>’, a personal name meaning ‘chief of harvest’. The Irish name was first Anglicized as <b>Mullover</b>, which was later assimilated to <i>Milford</i>. See also   Palmer  ."]},{"name":"Palmiere","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Italian Angelo, Dante, Enrico, Nicola, Salvatore, Vittorio.","Italian: from <i>palmiere</i> ‘palmer, pilgrim’. See   Palmer  ."]},{"name":"Parmer","meanings":["English: variant of   Palmer  .","Indian (northern states): variant of   Parmar  ."]},{"name":"Palmore","meanings":["Probably an altered form of English   Palmer   or an Americanized form of South German   Balmer  ."]}]},{"name":"John","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["form of   John  , also used quite frequently in the English-speaking world. In Northern Ireland it is sometimes found as a variant of   Ewan ."],"variants":[]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705188,"age":0,"year":"1224","julianDay":2168117,"title":"France Declares War on England","description":"France declared war on England as Louis VIII of France attacked Poitou and northern Gascony.","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705189,"age":35,"year":"1259","julianDay":2180901,"title":"100 Years of Conflict Between England and France Ends","description":"Treaty of Paris was signed on December 4, 1259, which ended 100 years of conflict between England and France.","url":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Treaty_of_Paris_(1259)","urlTitle":"Wikipedia - Treaty of Paris 1259","jurisdictionLevel":2}],"lifeSummary":"When John Palmer II was born in 1224, in Gloucester, Gloucestershire, England, his father, Sir John Palmer I, was 26 and his mother, Lady Constance Folfre, was 21. He married Amicia De Clopton in 1246, in Gloucestershire, England, United Kingdom. They were the parents of at least 2 sons. He died in 1276, in his hometown, at the age of 52."},"et":{"1224–1276":"1224–1276","1229–1270":"1229–1270","1250–1310":"1250–1310","1252–Male":